Thesis 2: Physics Strand
Title:
Information as Physical: Mass-Energy Equivalence, Holographic Boundaries, and Gravitational Consequences in a 12-Dimensional Framework
Core Question:
If information has thermodynamic cost and energy is equivalent to mass (E=mc²), what are the physical and gravitational implications of treating information as a real, boundary-encoded entity in extreme gravitational environments?
Key Objectives:

Develop the implications of E=mc² + information thermodynamics for the idea that information can carry effective mass and influence spacetime geometry.
Examine how the holographic principle and Loop Quantum Gravity’s discrete structures allow information to be preserved and redirected during high-curvature events (black hole horizons, quantum bounces).
Explore the “double flick” (inbound processing under time dilation + outbound axial release) as a physically meaningful information-redirection mechanism.
Investigate whether the drive toward coherence (Ψ_Final = 1) can be given a physical interpretation in terms of information gaining stable, coherent gravitational and geometric form.

Methodology:
Theoretical physics with emphasis on black hole thermodynamics, the holographic principle, Loop Quantum Gravity, and quantum information theory. Careful distinction between established results and speculative extensions.
Contribution:
Advances a physically grounded account of information as having mass and gravitational influence, while remaining in dialogue with the theological and computational strands of the model.
